    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A very common tactic is to limit the scope of indemnification to only claims arising from your *negligence* or actual *infringement* of intellectual property. You can also try to cap your liability, putting a dollar limit on how much you'd have to pay, perhaps tying it to the total project fee. Furthermore, insist that the clause should only indemnify them against third-party claims that are *directly* caused by your breach of contract, not just any general business risk they might face. Remember, a narrow, specific clause is much safer than a broad, sweeping one.",
      "source": "target",
